1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 {[%csl Bc3,Bd3,Bf3][%cal Bc2c3,Bb1a3,Ba3c2,Bf1d3,Bg1f3] White's ideal set-up is Bd3 Na3-Nc2 securing the pawn on d4 with Nc2 and Nf3. White's pawn chain c3-d4-e5 gives them more space and leaves Black with a cramped position. With e5, White controls the square f6, making it hard for Black to find a good square for Ng8. Black's bishop on c8 is notoriously bad, being hemmed in by the pawn chain f7-e6-d5. Black often tries to put pressure on the pawn on d4 with c5-Nc6-Qb6.} c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 (5... Qb6 {is called the Hector Variation and the subject of the first chapter,}) (5... Bd7 {is the Advance Variation and is covered in the second chapter.}) 6. Bd3 cxd4 7. O-O $5 {We sacrifice the pawn on d4 for a lead in development and more space. The modern engines believe White has more than sufficient compensation for the pawn. In practice, it is easier to attack than to defend so we prefer to be on the White side. The variation was named after the Swedish GM Johnny Hector who has been playing this line since 2007. More recently this line has been used by the 16th World Champion Magnus Carlsen, GM Maxime Vachier Lagrave and GM Gawain Jones. The opening is featured in Gawain Jones' excellent Coffeehouse Repertoire - Volume 2. This book has been an important reference work for this mini-course. This course has been designed for club players: the lines have been chosen and prioritized based on the Lichess Rapid and Classical games database (rating 1600 and up) . As a result, you will learn what you as a club player will face most likely over the board. It has been a deliberate choice to keep the book small (approximately 20 variations and 10 puzzles) . The idea is to learn these 20 variations and the associated ideas with high accuracy and cover over 80% of what you will face over the board. The idea is not to win based on better opening memorization but to get unbalanced, attacking positions that are fun to play. This course has been a cooperation between Fide Candidate Master Han Schut and Ben Davar. Ben Davar is an English major, who lives in NYC and is an avid chess player. As a club player and writer, he was responsible for clear and succinct comments. CM Han Schut selected the variations and was responsible for the overall quality assurance and final editing of the mini-course. Finally, the analysis was done using Stockfish 15.1 at depth 30 or higher where necessary supported by a second opinion by Leela Chess Zero 0.29.} *

