1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 (5... Bd7 {is the signature move for the Advance Variation. Black does not put immediate pressure on d4 with}) (5... Qb6 {but develops their bishop first.}) 6. Be2 ({Why do we not play} 6. Bd3 {as in the Hector-variation? In the Hector-variation we take on c5 after Bd7: /img/diagrams/38141-1679750002.pngPosition after 6... Bd7 White plays 7. dxc5}) ({Yet if we play} 6. Bd3 {in the Advance-variation, Black can play} cxd4 {first, and after} 7. cxd4 Qb6 {we no longer transpose.}) ({Can we first take on c5 to transpose to the Hector?} 6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. Bd3 {and now} Nge7 {is possible as without Qb6, b4 is no longer trapping Bc5} 8. O-O Ng6 9. Re1 Qc7 10. Qe2 f6 {and Black is taking over. The disadvantage of 5... Bd7 is that it gives White an extra move to organize their defense of pawn d4.}) *

