[PlyCount "14"]
[EventDate "2023.??.??"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 {Let's discuss the characteristics and plans associated with the French Advance pawn structure without White trading on c5. We have a closed position with a fixed pawn structure. White has a spatial advantage, the pawn on e5 is in enemy territory and controls d6 and f6. White's ideal setup is Bd3 and Na3-Nc2 securing the pawn on d4 and with maximum activity for the bishop. Black's light-squared bishop on c8 is considered 'bad' as it is hemmed in by the pawn chain f7-e6-d5. Black has difficulties completing their development due to the lack of space and the fact that f6 is not available for the g8-knight. Bf8 and Ng8 are often in each other's way (after Bc5 Nge7 Black has to be careful that their bishop will not be trapped after b4.) White's plans 1. Attack Black's king after O-O with the Greek Gift Bxh7 followed by Ng5+ or using a rook lift bringing the rook to g3 and bringing additional attackers. If the Black king stays in the middle, open the position with c3-c4 and sometimes more violently with Re1-Nxd5-e6 2. Continue to restrict the harmonious development of Black's pieces by threatening to trap them, by chasing them and for example by playing h4 after Nge7 to kick the knight back after Ne7-g6 with h4-h5. 3. A standard plan for White in the French Advance variation is to play f2-f4-f5 attacking the base of Black's pawn chain or even f2-f4-f5-f6 with a powerful kingside attack. This plan is only available if we move our f3 knight. Black's plans 1. Attack the pawn on d4 with c5, Nc6, Qb6 and sometimes Ne7-Nf5. Sometimes create counterplay on the c-file with Rc8 Nb4 threatening to invade on c2. 3. Challenge White's center with f7-f6 4. If Black castles long then they can initiate a kingside attack with h6-g5 or f6-g5. 4. Slow down White's attack with f7-f5. 5. Trade the 'bad' light-squared bishop on c8 with Bd7-Bb5 or b6-Ba6} Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bd7 7. dxc5 Bxc5 {Now that White has taken on c5 it is important for White to control the d4-square for instance by playing Nbd2-Nb3-Nd4 and sometimes Rd1.} *

