{The relative importance of this variation: HIGH  * 5... Qb6 52% after 5.Nf3  * 6... Bd7 52% after 6.Bd3  * 8... Nge7 35% after 8. O-O} 1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bd7 $6 (6... f6 $6 {does not go well with Qb6 and after} 7. O-O Bd7 8. Nbd2 $16 {White is better. Black's king is too exposed to go pawn hunting. For example} cxd4 9. cxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Nf3 Qb6 12. b4 $1 {. For the price of one pawn, White has a big lead in development and open lines for their pieces. Be3 and Nd4 are most likely White's next two moves, chasing Black's queen and threatening Qh5+. SF15.1: 1.5}) 7. dxc5 $1 {[%csl Bb6][%cal Bc5b6] Preparing a quick queenside expansion with b4-Na3-Rb1-c4. Black is underdeveloped and their pieces lack space. White can develop their initiative with tempo.} Bxc5 {[%csl Yf2][%cal Yc5f2,Yb6f2,Be1f2]} (7... Qc7 8. O-O Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 Qc7 11. b4 {SF15:+1 Black has lost too much time and has difficulty completing their development.}) 8. O-O {[%csl Bf2][%cal Bg1f2,Bf1f2,Yc5f2,Yb6f2] Defending the pawn on f2 by castling.} Nge7 $2 {Played in 35% of games in this position! Now the bishop on c5 gets trapped.} 9. b4 {[%csl Bc5][%cal Bb4c5]} Z0 ({Trapping the bishop on c5. SF15:+3 Black can give up a piece for two pawns} 9... Bxb4 10. cxb4 Nxb4 {but after} 11. a4 {planning Ba3 White has a winning position.}) *

