{The relative importance of this variation: HIGH  * 5... Qb6 52% after 5.Nf3  * 6... Bd7 52% after 6. Bd3  * 8... a5 24% after 8. O-O} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bd7 7. dxc5 $1 Bxc5 8. O-O a5 {[%cal Rb2b4] Played in 24% of the games after 8. O-O. Black prevents b4.} (8... f6 {the sharpest approach but only played in 5% of the games.} 9. b4 Be7 10. Re1 fxe5 $2 {played in 77% of the games.} 11. b5 $1 e4 12. bxc6 bxc6 13. Ne5 exd3 14. Qh5+ {SF15:+2}) 9. Qe2 {[%csl Rb6,Rc5,Rf2][%cal Rc5f2,Rb6f2][%mdl 32768]} ({The move} 9. Qe2 {gives us the best response to} f6 {with} 10. c4 $1 {opening up Black's centre.}) ({After} 9. Nbd2 f6 10. Qe2 fxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Qxe5 Nf6 {Black threatens} 13. Z0 Bxf2+ 14. Rxf2 Qxf2+ 15. Kxf2 Ng4+ {with a double attack on Qe5 and Kf2. After h3 O-O Black is fine.}) ({Not} 9. Re1 $2 {because of} Bxf2+ {.}) 9... Nge7 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Rb2b4,Gg8e7,Ge7g6] Black continues their plan: now that b4 has been stopped, they want to complete development with Nge7-Ng6.} (9... f6 {If Black decides to delay developing the knight, then we immediately open the center with the explosive c3-c4!} 10. c4 $14 {for example:} d4 11. exf6 Nxf6 12. Bf4 O-O 13. Nbd2 Rae8 14. Ne5 {SF15:+1}) 10. Nbd2 {If Black lets us, we will play Nb3 gaining absolute control over d4.} Ng6 {[%csl Be7,Bb3][%cal Bc5e7,Bd2b3]} (10... a4 11. b4 axb3 12. Nxb3 Ng6 13. h4 $16 {or}) (10... a4 11. b4 axb3 12. Nxb3 Ba3 13. Rb1 Qc7 14. Nbd4 {and White has Nb5 next. Black can not castle because of the Greek Gift Bxh7.}) 11. Nb3 Be7 ({Black doesn't want to give up their good bishop.} 11... O-O 12. Nxc5 Qxc5 13. h4 $16 {SF15: +1 White has the bishop pair and h5 coming, while Black still struggles with the passive bishop on d7.}) 12. Nbd4 $14 {[%csl Gc4,Rd5][%cal Gc3c4,Gg2g3,Rg6f4,Rg6h4,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] 'White has a pleasant game with good central control' GM Gawain Jones. Evaluation: SF15:+1} Z0 ({Some sample lines to show what can happen in practice:} 12... O-O 13. h4 Nxh4 $2 14. Nxh4 Bxh4 15. Qh5 {SF15:+5 12...Qc7 13.Re1 defending the pawn on e5. 13...O-O 14.h4 SF15:+2}) *

