{The relative importance of this Variation: MEDIUM  * 5... Qb6 52% after 5.Nf3  * 6... Bd7 52% after 6. Bd3  * 8... Qc7 16% after 8. O-O} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bd7 $6 ({Black's most popular move played 52% of the time. We reach the main course position after} 6... cxd4 7. O-O {.}) 7. dxc5 $1 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Gc5b6] Preparing a quick queenside expansion with b4-Na3-Rb1-c4. Black is underdeveloped and their pieces lack space. White can develop their initiative with tempo.} Bxc5 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gc5f2,Gb6f2] With a twofold attack on f2.} 8. O-O {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gg1f2,Gf1f2]} Qc7 {[%cal Yc6e5,Yc7e5]} ({Protecting the pawn on f2 and bringing the king into safety. Black's most popular moves:} 8... Nge7 $2 {34%}) (8... a5 {24%}) (8... Qc7 {16%}) (8... Nh6 {9%}) (8... f6 {5%}) ({The third most popular move in this position. Qc7 and Nc6 now attack the pawn on e5. Furthermore, Qc7 frees the square b6 for Bc5 making it possible for Black to complete their development with Nge7 and O-O as after b4 the bishop is no longer trapped.} 8... Nh6 9. b4 Be7 10. Bxh6 gxh6 11. Qd2 {and now the only way for Black to save the pawn on h6 is the unnatural} Bf8 $16 {SF15:+1.}) 9. b4 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Yb4c5][%mdl 32768]} ({Attacking Bc5.} 9. Re1 {is an alternative.}) 9... Bb6 10. Re1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf3e5,Ge1e5] Defending the pawn on e5.} Nge7 (10... a6 11. Na3 Nge7 12. Rb1 {transposes.}) 11. Na3 {[%csl Yb5,Yc7,Yd6][%cal Ya3b5,Yb5d6,Yb5c7] White develops their knight with tempo, threatening Nb5, attacking Qc7 and threatening Nd6+. Na3 clears the square b1 for Ra1 and keeps the diagonal c1-h6 open for Bc1.} a6 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Ga6b5] Protecting the square b5.} 12. Rb1 $16 {[%csl Gb4,Yc4][%cal Gb1b4,Yc3c4]} Z0 ({White is better SF15:+1 and now that the pawn on b4 is protected by Rb1, White is ready to play c3-c4. Black most often continues} 12... Ng6 {attacking the pawn on e5 for a third time. White ignores the threat and after} 13. c4 Ncxe5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. c5 {is winning because of the dual threat Bf4, pinning Ne5 to Qc7 and cxb6 . Please note that after 12...Ng6 13.c4 dxc4 14.Nxc4 White is winning after 14...O-O 15.Nxb6 Qxb6 16.Bxg6 hxg6 17.Qxd7 Rfd8 18.Be3! . After 12...O-O Black is on the receiving end of the thematic Greek Gift: 13.Bxh7 Kxh7 14.Ng5 Kg6 15.h4 and White wins.}) *

