{The relative importance of this variation: HIGH  * 5... Qb6 52% after 5.Nf3  * 6... cxd4 35% after 6.Bd3  * 7... dxc3 60% after 7. O-O  * 8... Bd7 33% after 8. Nxc3  * 9... Bb4 32% after 9. Re1} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3 cxd4 (6... Bd7 {is played in 52% of the games and}) (6... cxd4 {in 35% of the games. The move}) (6... cxd4 {is more challenging and the main line of the Hector variation.}) 7. O-O $5 {[%mdl 32768] Instead of immediately recapturing on d4, we accelerate our development by castling kingside and offering Black a pawn in exchange for a lead in development and more space.} (7. cxd4 {is the well-known Milner-Barry variation.}) 7... dxc3 {Played in 59% of the games. Black, oblivious to the danger, accepts the gambit. More fun for us!} 8. Nxc3 {Black's most popular responses are:  * 8... Bd7 33%  * 8... Nge7 25%  * 8... a6 17%  * 8... Bb4 9%} Bd7 {Black continues their development.} 9. Re1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge1e5,Gf3e5] Adding a defender to our e5 pawn.} Bb4 $6 {Black's most popular move in this position 32% .} (9... f6 $2 {Played only 1% of the time, but allows White to open the position immediately with} 10. Nxd5 $1 exd5 11. exf6+ Kd8 12. Ng5 {and White wins because of the threat Nf7+.}) (9... Nb4 {Black's choice in 5% of the games, attacking the bishop on d3} 10. Bb1 Bc5 11. Rf1 {followed by a3-b4. Notice that after} Ne7 {we are winning Bc5 with} 12. a3 Nbc6 13. Na4 Qa5 14. b4 {.}) 10. a3 {We encourage Black to give up their good bishop.} Bxc3 (10... Ba5 $4 11. b4 {trapping the bishop.}) (10... Bc5 $4 {This allows Na4 double attack. Black doesn't have time to take the rook because the queen is under attack.} 11. Na4 Bxf2+ 12. Kf1) 11. bxc3 Nge7 12. a4 $16 {GM Gawain Jones: ''Black's dark squares are chronically weak. There's also the rather big problem that he's no closer to getting his king to safety as the Greek Gift Bxh7 looms large.' White's compensation for the sacrificed pawn is long-term. Black will have a hard time finding safety for the king. White has the bishop pair and active pieces. After the bishop moves to a3 it is an especially strong piece, as it is unopposed. White can prepare c4 to break up Black's center. SF15:+1} *

