{The relative importance of this variation: MEDIUM  * 5... Qb6 52% after 5.Nf3  * 6... cxd4 35% after 6.Bd3  * 7... Bd7 34% after 7. O-O  * 8... Nge7 19% after 8. Re1  * 9... h6 18% after 9. h4} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3 cxd4 ({The move} 6... cxd4 {is played in 35% of the games. This is the correct time for Black to exchange in the center.}) (6... Bd7 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. O-O {transposes to our first three variations [/variation/16848818]}) 7. O-O Bd7 $1 {Black does not accept the gambit and avoids the whole headache by simply developing.} 8. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e5,Gf3e5][%mdl 32768] We keep the tension in the center and add another defender to the pawn on e5 . Most frequently Black transposes here to the ( 8...dxc3 line 64% We will now consider 8...Nge7 , played in 19% of the games. 8...Bc5 6%} Nge7 (8... Bc5 9. b4 {and White is better.}) (8... dxc3 9. Nxc3 {transposes to these variations [/variation/16848815]}) 9. h4 h6 ({As usual, we play h4 to threaten to kick the knight after Ne7-g6. Now the most frequently played move} 9... dxc3 10. Nxc3 {transposes to this variation [/variation/24426100]. We will consider 9...h6 . 9...Nf5 and 9...a6 Finally, Black also has 9...Rc8 10.h5 h6 11.a3 a6 12.b4 dxc3 13.Nxc3 Nxb4 14.Na4 Bxa4 15.Qxa4 Nbc6 . GM Gawain Jones: 'After 16.Bd2 Qc7 17.Qg4 White has beautiful open lines for his pieces, while Black is really struggling for a plan.'}) {FM Kamil Plichta's recommendation in his LTR Plichta's French Defense.} 10. h5 {GM Gawain Jones: 'Both sides are playing a waiting game, making generally useful moves while waiting for the opponent to resolve the c3-d4 tension.'} Rc8 11. a3 {[%csl Gb4,Rc3][%cal Ga3b4,Rd4c3]} ({A novelty suggested by GM Gawain Jones. With} 11. a3 {, White prepares to play b4 and pawn b4 will continue to be defended after the dxc3.}) 11... a6 (11... dxc3 12. Nxc3 Na5 13. Rb1 $14) 12. b4 {As planned.} dxc3 13. Nxc3 Nxb4 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Rc8c3] With a discovered attack on Nc3.} (13... Nf5 $2 14. Nxd5 $1 exd5 15. e6 $1 {Interfering with Bd7's defense of Nf5} Bxe6 16. Bxf5 {SF15:+2}) 14. Na4 $1 {Attacking the queen while Nb4 remains under attack. Black is forced to exchange on a4 and then interpose with Nb4-Nc6.} Bxa4 15. Qxa4+ Nbc6 16. Bd2 {[%csl Ga5,Gb4,Gc3,Gd2,Ge3,Gf4,Gg5]} Z0 ({White has full compensation for the two pawns. GM Gawain Jones: 'After} 16... Qc7 17. Qg4 {White has beautiful open lines for his pieces, while Black is really struggling for a plan.'}) *

