{The relative importance of this variation: MEDIUM  * 5... Bd7 17% after 5.Nf3  * 6... Qb6 33% after 6. Be2  * 7... cxd4 35% after 7. O-O  * 10... Qc7 51% after 10. Na4} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 {The signature move of the Advance variation.} 6. Be2 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Why do we not play} 6. Bd3 {as in the Hector-variation? In the Hector-variation we take on c5 after Bd7: /img/diagrams/38141-1679750002.pngPosition after 6... Bd7 White plays 7. dxc5}) ({Yet if we play} 6. Bd3 {in the Advance-variation, Black can play} cxd4 {first and after} 7. cxd4 Qb6 {we no longer transpose.}) ({Can we first take on c5 to transpose to the Hector?} 6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. Bd3 {and now} Nge7 {is possible as without Qb6, b4 is no longer trapping Bc5} 8. O-O Ng6 9. Re1 Qc7 10. Qe2 f6 {and Black is taking over. The disadvantage of 5... Bd7 is that it gives White an extra move to organize their defense of pawn d4.}) 6... Qb6 {Played in 33% of the games. Black adds pressure to the d4 pawn, but White has time to castle and keep the d4-e5 pawn chain.} 7. O-O {White's plan is dxc5 followed by Be3 chasing the queen and developing a piece or b4 chasing the queen and gaining space.} cxd4 (7... Nge7 8. dxc5 Qxc5 9. Be3 Qa5 $14 {White is slightly better and planning Nbd2-c4 opening up the position with the Black king still in the middle.}) 8. cxd4 {[%csl Rb6,Rc6,Gd1,Gf3][%cal Gf3d4,Gd1d4]} Nge7 {[%csl Yf5,Yd4][%cal Ye7f5,Yf5d4,Yc6d4,Yb6d4] The knight is heading to f5 to put pressure on the pawn on d4.} 9. Nc3 {White will defend by chasing an attacker with Nc3-Na4.} Nf5 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Yf5d4,Yc6d4,Yb6d4]} (9... a6 10. Na4 Qa7 11. Be3 Nf5 12. Bd3 {and White is slightly better.}) 10. Na4 {[%csl Yb6][%cal Ya4b6] Chasing the queen, one of the attackers of pawn d4.} Qc7 11. g4 {Kicking back Black's most active piece.} Nfe7 {[%csl Re7]} (11... Nh6 12. h3 Be7 13. Be3 O-O 14. Rc1 {SF15:+1}) 12. Be3 h5 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gg4g5] Black wants to undermine pawn g4 and win back the f5 square for their knight.} 13. g5 {We are willing to create a hole on f5 because we will challenge the Knight immediately Bd3-Bxf5.} Nf5 14. Bd3 g6 (14... Nxe3 $6 15. fxe3 $16 {White now has a semi-open f-file for Rf1, and pawn e3 to support the strong central pawn chain e3-d4-e5. The Black king has not found safety yet and after O-O-O we will attack the king with Rc1-a3-b4.}) 15. Bxf5 gxf5 {[%csl Rd5,Rd7,Re6,Rf7]} 16. Rc1 {[%csl Ba3,Bb4,Bc5][%cal Ba2a3,Bb2b4,Ba4c5] White is better with more space and a lead in development. Black's king has not found safety yet and White is planning to expand on the queenside with a3-b4 and a later Nc5. The bishop on d7 is still passive. SF15:+1} *

