{The relative importance of this variation: MEDIUM  * 4... cxd4 9% after 4.c3  * 5... Nc6 56% after 5.cxd4  * 6... Bb4+ 30% after 6. Nf3} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 cxd4 $6 {It is premature for Black to resolve the central tension so early. Now White can develop their knight to the ideal square c3 in one move.} 5. cxd4 {[%mdl 32768] White now has no problems developing pieces to their most active squares Nc3 and securing the pawn on d4.} Nc6 6. Nf3 Bb4+ {The most common move in this position and played in 30% of the games.} 7. Nc3 Nge7 8. Bd3 O-O {Played in 33% of the games after 8. Bd3. Black completed their development but now we can play the thematic Greek Gift sacrifice.} 9. Bxh7+ {Gaining access to the king.} Kxh7 10. Ng5+ {Bringing Nf3 into the attack with tempo and opening the d1-h5 diagonal for the queen to join the attack as well.} Kg6 (10... Kg8 11. Qh5 Re8 12. Qh7+ Kf8 13. Qh8+ Ng8 14. Nh7+ Ke7 15. Bg5+ {wins. After} f6 16. Qxg7# {is mate and 15...Nf6 16.Qxg7 Kd7 17.Nxf6 Kc7 18.O-O is SF15:+6.}) 11. h4 {SF15: +8 White is threatening h5+ Kh6 Nxf7 winning the Black queen and Qd3+ with a mating attack supported by g4 if Black interposes with Nf5 and sometimes Rg1 if White has played gxf5.} (11. h4 {is simpler than}) (11. Qd3+ Nf5 12. g4 f6) ({or} 11. Qg4 f5 12. Qg3 f4 13. Qg4 Qe8 {.}) *

