{The relative importance of this variation: MEDIUM  * 4... Qb6 15% after 4. c3  * 5... Bd7 13% after 5. Nf3} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Qb6 {[%csl Bb5][%cal Bc8d7,Bd7b5] Black's idea is to exchange their 'bad bishop' as fast as possible with Bd7-Bb5. However, this plan does not put pressure on d4, which allows us to develop naturally.} 5. Nf3 {[%mdl 32768]} Bd7 {[%csl Bb5][%cal Bd7b5] The bishop is heading to b5 where it will be exchanged for our light-squared bishop.} (5... Nc6 {, played in 82% of the games, transposes to our main lines.}) 6. Bd3 Bb5 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Yb5d3]} 7. dxc5 $1 {[%csl Yb6][%cal Yc5b6]} Bxc5 8. b4 {If Black just returns with Be7/Bf8, White has a comfortable advantage due to a lead in development, the strong e5 pawn, and a much safer king.} Bxd3 (8... Be7 $2 {The Bishop is passive on e7--Black is letting us play Be3 without a fight.} 9. Be3 Qa6 10. Bxb5+ Qxb5 11. a4 Qc4 12. Qd2 $16 {White is ready to play Na3 and O-O, connecting rooks and completing development. White is slightly better.}) (8... Bxf2+ $2 9. Ke2 Bxd3+ 10. Qxd3 f6 11. Rf1 Ne7 {.}) 9. Qxd3 Bxf2+ $2 (9... Be7 10. O-O Nc6 11. a4 Qc7 12. Na3 a6 13. Re1 $14) 10. Ke2 {[%cal Rf2h4,Rf2b6] All the bishop's escape squares are controlled by White. We will continue with Rf1 to add a second attacker without creating a new escape square for the bishop on f2.} Nc6 11. Rf1 Z0 ({White is winning SF15:+2. Black's best try is} 11... Bh4 12. Nxh4 Nxe5 {, getting a second pawn for the bishop, but the compensation is insufficient.}) *

