{This game was played in the second round of the U.S. Women's Chess Championship on October 7, 2021.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3 cxd4 7. O-O Bd7 8. Re1 Nge7 9. h4 a6 10. h5 {We are following 5... Qb6 6... cxd4 7... Bd7 9... a6 [/variation/22536529].} h6 ({In that variation, Black continues} 10... g6 {which is GM Anish Giri's recommendation. White continues} 11. Nbd2) 11. Qe2 ({GM Gawain Jones recommends:} 11. a3 Rc8 {11...f5? 12.exf6 gxf6 13.cxd4+-} 12. b4 dxc3 13. Nxc3 Nxb4 14. Na4 Bxa4 15. Qxa4+ Nbc6 16. Bd2 Qc7 17. Qg4 $13) 11... f5 12. exf6 ({Better} 12. Na3 {and develop on the queenside. The move 11. f5 makes it hard for Black to complete her development. Where is Ne7 going? How is Black getting her king into safety?}) 12... gxf6 13. cxd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxd4 15. Be3 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Ye3d4]} Qe5 $2 ({Now the queen will continue to be chased and White will develop all her pieces with tempo. Better} 15... Qh4 {.}) 16. Nd2 Rg8 17. f4 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Yf4e5]} Qd6 18. Qf2 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Ye3c5]} Rc8 19. Rad1 Bc6 $2 {Black misses White's threat of Bh7 followed immediately by the double attack Ne4.} (19... f5 {or}) (19... Kf7 {would have maintained the balance in the game.}) 20. Bh7 {[%csl Yg8][%cal Yh7g8] Clearing the d-file with tempo for the deadly threat Ne4 with a double attack on Qd6 and f6.} Rg7 {[%csl Yh7][%cal Yg7h7]} 21. Ne4 {[%csl Yf6,Yd6][%cal Ye4f6,Ye4d6,Yd1d6]} Qc7 22. Bb6 {[%csl Yc7][%cal Yb6c7]} ({Winning the Black queen but even stronger was} 22. Nxf6+ Kf7 23. f5 {.}) 22... dxe4 23. Bxc7 Rxh7 {SF15:+2 Black has B+N+p against Q but in addition, Black's pieces lack coordination and Black's king is unsafe. White shows good technique in converting her advantage.} 24. Bd6 Rg7 25. Rc1 Nf5 26. Bxf8 Kxf8 {[%csl Yc8][%cal Yc1c8]} 27. Rxe4 Rd8 (27... Bxe4 28. Rxc8+ Kf7 29. Rc7+ Kg8 30. Rxg7+ Kxg7 {is an easy win.}) 28. Rxc6 bxc6 29. Rxe6 Ng3 30. Rxf6+ Ke7 31. Qc5+ Kxf6 32. Qe5+ Kf7 33. Qc7+ 1-0

