{This game was played in the sixth round of the 15th Khazar Cup in 2017. White's play is a good example of how to attack an uncastled king in the advanced French structure.} 1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nge7 6. Na3 cxd4 {Black decides to clarify the pawn structure before continuing.} 7. cxd4 {Please note that in the trainable line 5...Nge7 6.Na3 [/variation/%2024411043] Black plays 6...Nf5 first and then cxd4, but the move order is not important and we transpose back to trainable variation.} Nf5 {Black puts the king knight on its most active square where it pressures d4.} 8. Nc2 {White also manoeuvres his knight to a better square. The knight on c2 protects d4 and prepares a potential queenside expansion b2-b4.} Bd7 {The game follows the variation 5...Nge7 6.Na3 [/variation/24411043] up to move eight. In the game, Black plays 8... Bd7 and our trainable variation continues 8... Be7.} 9. Bd3 $1 Qb6 ({Developing the Bishop to its most active square. Note that} 9... Qb6 10. O-O {tactically defends the pawn on d4. What if White played the more quiet looking 9. Be2? 9.Be2?! Be7 Black does not want to play Qb6 now as d4 is adequately defended and instead prepares to castle to safety. 10.O-O O-O =}) (9... Be7 {Might have been slightly better, getting ready to castle next move.} 10. O-O O-O 11. g4 {White is now ready to start a kingside attack.} Nh4 12. Nxh4 Bxh4 13. f4 $14 {White has more space on the kingside, so it makes sense to play on this side of the board. Bd3 is a great attacking piece, and White can increase the energy of their army with Kh1-Rg1, and Rf1-Rf3.}) 10. O-O a5 (10... Nfxd4 $4 {Black can't take on d4 because of the following sequence.} 11. Nfxd4 Nxd4 12. Be3 {Pinning Nd4 to Qb6.} Bc5 13. b4 {Attacks a defender of the pinned piece, and now Black can't save the knight.}) 11. Kh1 $1 {White's king was lined up with Qb6 on the a7-g1 diagonal. This is an excellent prophylactic move, as it enables White to play Be3 and/or f4 with a much safer king.} Rc8 ({Black is not hurrying to castle kingside, he will not be safe there. For example} 11... Be7 12. g4 Nh6 13. Rg1 O-O 14. Bxh6 gxh6 15. g5 {SF15:+4 Note how Black's lack of space prevents him from bringing defenders to the kingside. The Bd7 is blocked from participating on the kingside due to pawn e6 and Nc6 lacking a road back to the kingside, Ne7 to g6 would be a strong defender, closing the g-file and the b1-h7 diagonal, but Black has no time for such manoeuvres.}) (11... Be7 12. g4 Nh6 13. Rg1 O-O {?} 14. Bxh6 gxh6 15. g5) 12. Rb1 {White overprotects b2 so that Bc1 is free to move without dropping a pawn.} Nb4 {Black would love to take Bd3 off the board--trades favour the side with less space. Fewer pieces means more available squares} ({Lupulescu played this position on the Black side three years earlier and continued:} 12... h6 13. Bd2 Be7 14. b4 axb4 15. Nxb4 Nxb4 16. Bxb4 Bxb4 17. a3 Qa7 18. Rxb4 Ne7 19. Qb3 Rc7 20. Rb1 O-O {½-½ Efimenko,Z (2649)-Lupulescu,C (2630) Bundesliga 2014 with equality}) 13. Nxb4 axb4 (13... Bxb4 {Black probably didn't recapture with the Bishop because he wanted to keep the e7 square for Nf5, since after} 14. a3 Be7 {Black has to worry about g4 Nh4 potentially, though in this position White has stronger moves.}) 14. a4 $1 {Another strong move. Taking en passant opens up White's pieces, while ignoring a4 allows White to continue with Ra1 and/or b3, blocking up the Queenside before continuing play in the center and on the kingside.} Nxd4 $6 ({White is already better but} 14... Nxd4 {allows White to build up a strong initiative with a couple of forcing moves.}) (14... bxa3 {activates Rb1} 15. bxa3 Qa7 16. Qe2 Nxd4 {16...Be7 17.Qb2 $16}) (14... Be7 15. Ra1 {and now} O-O $2 16. g4 Nh4 17. Nxh4 Bxh4 18. g5 {and White is winning.}) 15. Be3 {[%cal Gf3d4,Ge3d4] Pinning Nd4. Please note that the move Kh1 pays off here, as Black would have the defensive resource Nxf3+ before retreating with the queen. But with the king on h1, this does not come with a check and Black loses the Queen.} Bc5 16. Nxd4 Bxd4 17. Qg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4g7,Gg4d4] Double attacking Bd4 and g7} Bxe3 18. Qxg7 Rf8 19. fxe3 Qxe3 ({One final mention of Kh1.} 19... Qxe3 {would come with check and win Bd3 if the king was on g1.}) 20. Bxh7 $16 {After all the exchanges, material is equal but White is clearly better SF15:+2 as Black's king is very unsafe. Even though Black exchanged 3 sets of minor pieces, White's remaining pieces are well coordinated (rooks are connected, control over f6, Q+B might coordinate on f7 at some point.} Rc4 21. h3 Rh4 $2 (21... Rf4 {Was necessary, fighting for control of the f file and f6 square.} 22. Rbe1 d4 23. Rg1 Qf2) 22. Rf6 Qxe5 23. Bg8 Rxh3+ 24. gxh3 Qe4+ 25. Kh2 Qe5+ 26. Kg1 Qd4+ 27. Kg2 Qe4+ 28. Rf3 Qxb1 29. Bxf7+ Rxf7 30. Qxf7+ Kd8 31. Qf8+ Kc7 32. Qc5+ Bc6 33. Rf7+ Kb8 34. Rf8+ Kc7 35. Qe7+ Bd7 36. Qc5+ Bc6 37. Qe7+ Bd7 38. Qxb4 Qg6+ 39. Qg4 Qh7 40. Qg3+ Kb6 41. Qe3+ Kc7 42. Qe5+ Kc6 43. Rf2 Kb6 44. Kh2 Bc6 45. b4 Bxa4 46. Qxe6+ Bc6 47. Qe3+ Kc7 48. Qe5+ Kb6 49. Qd4+ Kc7 50. Rg2 Bd7 51. Qc3+ Kd8 52. Qg3 Qe4 53. Qb8+ Ke7 54. Rf2 Bf5 55. Qxb7+ Ke6 56. Qc8+ 1-0

