[White "6. Model games"]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus vs. Terry"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C02"]
[PlyCount "65"]
[EventDate "2023.??.??"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

{GM Magnus Carlsen gifted us a model game with the Supercharged Milner-Barry Gambit on the publication date of this course through a thematic win over IM Renato Terry in the Chess.com Titled Tuesday. Carlsen first restricts the development of Black's pieces, especially Ne7, Bf8 and Rh8 and Black's king does not find a safe haven. Subsequently Carlsen opens up the position with the thematic c3-c4 push, activates all his pieces to the maximum including landing an octopus knight on d6 and a rook on the seventh rank. Black sacrifices his queen to stop White's onslaught but in the remaining position a passed pawn on d6 and the lack of activity and coordination of Black's pieces decide the game. See [ https://youtu.be/ZELHYcehaPg ] for an instructive video by Jozarov. Thanks Thomas_Logan_Ritchie for bringing the game and the video to our attention.} 1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 {We have entered the Advance Variation of the French Defense.} Qb6 5. Nf3 Bd7 {Black's plan with Qb6-Bd7 is to quickly exchange their 'bad' light squared bishop with a subsequent Bb5.} 6. Bd3 cxd4 (6... Bb5 {is variation 4... Qb6 5... Bd7 6... Bb5 [/variation/16909595].}) 7. O-O $5 {Carlsen wants a fight! 7. cxd4 and 7. Nxd4 are far more popular but Magnus has a different idea, offering Black the pawn on c3.} (7. Nxd4 Nc6 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. O-O Ne7 10. Nd2 $14) 7... Nc6 {IM Terry prioritizes development over material.} (7... dxc3 8. Nxc3 Ne7 {is our model game Carissa Yip vs. Anna Zatonskih [/variation/16862255].}) 8. Re1 {Through an unusual move order, we have arrived at the Hector Variation from Chapter 1!} Nge7 9. h4 $1 {The thematic response to Nge7 threatening to kick the knight back after Ng6 with h5.} a6 {GM Anish Giri's recommendation in his French LTR.} (9... dxc3 {Black should not help White accelerate their development and win time by chasing Qb6.} 10. Nxc3 a6 11. Na4 Qa7 12. Be3) 10. h5 h6 {Both sides keep the tension around c3-d4 alive and continue to develop their pieces. Black has not brought his king into safety and has difficulty completing the development of Ne7 and Bf8. We cover GM Giri's move} (10... g6 11. Nbd2 gxh5 12. Nb3 dxc3 13. bxc3 {in variation 5... Qb6 6... cxd4 7... Bd7 9... a6 [/variation/22536529].}) 11. Nbd2 {Magnus encourages his opponent to take on c3, splitting his queenside pawns. GM Gawain Jones suggests to continue now with} (11. a3 $146 {and after} Rc8 12. b4 dxc3 13. Nxc3 Nxb4 14. Na4 $1 {we have transposed to variation 5... Qb6 6... cxd4 7... Bd7 9... h6 [/variation/24553711].}) 11... dxc3 {Though White's queenside pawns look weak, the open b-file and c3-c4 break give Carlsen active play.} 12. bxc3 $14 {White is down a pawn but has more space and a lead in development. Black's king is still in the middle and White is going to open up lines to attack Black's king.} Qc7 13. c4 {A thematic way to break open the position.} Nb4 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gb4d3]} 14. Bf1 dxc4 15. Nxc4 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gc4d6] Threatening the devastating Nd6+ followed by Nf7+ with a double attack on Kd8 and Rh8.} Ned5 $16 {Wrong square for the knight.} (15... Nf5 {Was better, controlling d6.} 16. Bd2 Bc5 17. g4 b5 $14) 16. Bb2 {[%csl Gg7][%cal Gb2g7] X-raying the pawn on g7.} (16. Nd4 $1 {Was even stronger, with the brilliant idea} Bc5 17. Nd6+ Bxd6 18. exd6 {and now} Qxd6 $2 19. Nf5 $3 {exploiting the pin to bring more attackers. Black cannot defend. SF15: +4}) 16... Bc5 17. Nd6+ $1 Kf8 (17... Bxd6 18. exd6 Qxd6 {isn't any better. White will win both g7 and h6 pawns.} 19. a3 Nc6 20. Bxg7 Rg8 21. Bxh6 {SF15:+2}) 18. Qd2 $2 {This actually allows Black to get back into the game with a tricky defensive resource.} (18. Bd4 {threatening Rc1.} Bxd4 19. Nxd4 {SF15:+3}) 18... Qb6 $2 {Black misses the defensive resource Nc2 and now the attack continues.} (18... Nc2 $1 {Black could have fought back with Nc2! Luring the queen to the c-file with a double attack of the knight on White's two rooks.} 19. Qxc2 Bxd6 {Regaining the sacrificed piece with a discovery on Qc2.} 20. Qe4 $14) 19. Rab1 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Gb1b6] With an x-ray attack on Qb6.} Qa7 20. Bd4 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Rb1b4] Threatening Rxb4 as Bc5 is pinned.} Bxd4 21. Nxd4 {Rb1 is attacking Nb4 and eyeing pawn b7.} Qc5 22. a3 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Ga3b4]} Nc6 23. Rxb7 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Gb7d7]} Rd8 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Gd8d7]} (23... Qxd4 {No salvation in trading queens.} 24. Qxd4 Nxd4 25. Rxd7 Ne7 26. Rc1 Ndc6 27. f4 {SF15:+4 Black is playing without Rh8.}) 24. Nxc6 Bxc6 25. Rc1 {Winning Bc6 if the queen does not sacrifice herself at d6.} Qxd6 (25... Qxa3 26. Rxc6) 26. exd6 Bxb7 {Materially speaking Black is -1 but White has a passed pawn, Black's pieces lack coordination and Rh8 is still out of the game SF15:+6} 27. Qb2 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gb2b7]} Ba8 28. Bxa6 Kg8 29. Rc8 Rxc8 30. Bxc8 Kh7 31. d7 Nf6 32. Qc2+ Be4 33. Qc7 {And Black has to give up his knight to stop the promotion of the pawn on d7.} 1-0

